    {
      "@id": "gist:Commitment",
      "@type": "owl:Class",
      "owl:equivalentClass": {
        "@id": "_:ndfd66d7f0f4d459a8ec599499a65c2e2b34"
      },
      "rdfs:comment": [
        "NOTE: The manner in which a commitment is binding may vary. In a business context, we are typically interested in commitments that are legally binding.",
        "NOTE: A commitment is unilateral in that it is binding on only one party. This contrasts with gist:Agreement, which consists of commitments that bind two or more parties.",
        "DEFINITION: A promise made by a single party to one or more parties to do or not do something or act in a particular way.",
        "EXAMPLE: When signing an NDA, the signatory commits to keeping specified information confidential.",
        "NOTE: A single commitment may be made to multiple parties at once; it is a single commitment rather than multiple commitments if the same action would fulfill the obligation to all the parties simultaneously. For example, a performer makes a single commitment to hold a performance to all ticket purchasers; by holding the performance, the commitment to all parties is fulfilled in a single action.",
        "EXAMPLE: Upon selling a treasury bill, the U.S. government makes a commitment to pay the purchaser a stated amount of money at a stated time."
      ],
      "rdfs:isDefinedBy": {
        "@id": "https://w3id.org/semanticarts/ontology/gistCore14.1.0"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "Commitment",
      "rdfs:subClassOf": {
        "@id": "gist:Intention"
      },
      "skos:definition": "A promise made by a single party to one or more parties to do or not do something or act in a particular way.",
      "skos:example": [
        "When signing an NDA, the signatory commits to keeping specified information confidential.",
        "Upon selling a treasury bill, the U.S. government makes a commitment to pay the purchaser a stated amount of money at a stated time."
      ],
      "skos:prefLabel": "Commitment",
      "skos:scopeNote": [
        "A commitment is unilateral in that it is binding on only one party. This contrasts with gist:Agreement, which consists of commitments that bind two or more parties.",
        "A single commitment may be made to multiple parties at once; it is a single commitment rather than multiple commitments if the same action would fulfill the obligation to all the parties simultaneously. For example, a performer makes a single commitment to hold a performance to all ticket purchasers; by holding the performance, the commitment to all parties is fulfilled in a single action.",
        "The manner in which a commitment is binding may vary. In a business context, we are typically interested in commitments that are legally binding."
      ]
    },
